<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,969]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,265,330,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Male.</emphasis>
Thoracic and abdominal chaetotaxy as in 
<figureCitation box="[732,798,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1941,1965]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,197,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-23@6.[151,1436,181,1917]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–9. Indoceoplanetes (Indoceoplanetes) saburrata new species ex Coracina lineata ombriosa. 8, male habitus, dorsal and ventral views. 9, female habitus, dorsal and ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825553/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
; tergopleurites II–V with 1 
<emphasis box="[1104,1126,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">ss</emphasis>
on each side; tergopleurites VI–VII with 2 
<emphasis box="[317,339,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">ss</emphasis>
on each side; segment VI with 2 
<emphasis box="[711,736,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">ps</emphasis>
on each side. Basal apodeme rounded rectangular, lateral margins slightly concave (
<figureCitation box="[404,486,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,197,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[167,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Indoceoplanetes (Indoceoplanetes) saburrata new species ex Coracina lineata ombriosa. 10, male head, dorsal and ventral views. 11, male genitalia, dorsal view. 12, male mesosome, ventral view. 13, male paramere, dorsal view. 14, female subgenital plate and vulval margin, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825555" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825555/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Proximal mesosome small, rounded, without lateral bulges or extensions (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1422,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,197,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[167,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Indoceoplanetes (Indoceoplanetes) saburrata new species ex Coracina lineata ombriosa. 10, male head, dorsal and ventral views. 11, male genitalia, dorsal view. 12, male mesosome, ventral view. 13, male paramere, dorsal view. 14, female subgenital plate and vulval margin, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825555" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825555/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
), anterior margin convex. Mesosomal lobes more or less parallel. Distal margin of mesosome flat. Gonopore with antero-lateral extensions rounded. Dorsal fringe tilted posteriorly, without anterior thumb-like process. Chaetotaxy: 2–3 ventral 
<emphasis box="[287,359,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">gpmes</emphasis>
on each side of distal gonopore; 2 
<emphasis box="[759,824,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">lpmes</emphasis>
sensilla on each side on mesosomal lobes; 1–2 dorsal 
<emphasis box="[151,209,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">ames</emphasis>
on each side distal to dorsal fringe. Parameres and 
<emphasis box="[785,859,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">pst1–2</emphasis>
as in 
<figureCitation box="[926,1008,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,197,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[167,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Indoceoplanetes (Indoceoplanetes) saburrata new species ex Coracina lineata ombriosa. 10, male head, dorsal and ventral views. 11, male genitalia, dorsal view. 12, male mesosome, ventral view. 13, male paramere, dorsal view. 14, female subgenital plate and vulval margin, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825555" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825555/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
. Measurements as in 
<tableCitation box="[1248,1332,547,573]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="47.[151,239,457,483]" captionText="TABLE 1. Measurements (in mm) of species treated in this paper. Abbreviations used: TL = total length; HL = head length (along midline); HW = head width (at temples); PRW = prothorax width; PTW = pterothorax width; AW = abdominal width (at segment V). Note: many specimens had distorted abdomens, as noted below; consequently, the TL of many specimens could not be measured. Mean values are given in parentheses only where 10 or more individuals were measured. N = number of specimens examined." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,969]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,582,609]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Female.</emphasis>
Thoracic and abdominal chaetotaxy as in 
<figureCitation box="[759,825,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1941,1965]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,197,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-23@6.[151,1436,181,1917]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–9. Indoceoplanetes (Indoceoplanetes) saburrata new species ex Coracina lineata ombriosa. 8, male habitus, dorsal and ventral views. 9, female habitus, dorsal and ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825553/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
; segment VI with 2 
<emphasis box="[1047,1072,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">ps</emphasis>
on each side. Subgenital plate as in 
<figureCitation box="[179,261,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,197,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[167,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Indoceoplanetes (Indoceoplanetes) saburrata new species ex Coracina lineata ombriosa. 10, male head, dorsal and ventral views. 11, male genitalia, dorsal view. 12, male mesosome, ventral view. 13, male paramere, dorsal view. 14, female subgenital plate and vulval margin, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825555" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825555/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
; distal margin broadly flattened. Vulval margin gently rounded to somewhat flattened medianly, with 2–3 short, slender 
<emphasis box="[311,355,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vms</emphasis>
and 1 short, thorn-like 
<emphasis box="[622,656,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vss</emphasis>
on each side; 4–7 slender 
<emphasis box="[958,995,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vos</emphasis>
on each side of subgenital plate; distal 2–3 
<emphasis box="[200,237,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vos</emphasis>
on each side distal to 
<emphasis box="[486,520,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vss</emphasis>
and near 
<emphasis box="[630,674,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vms</emphasis>
, but substantially longer than 
<emphasis box="[1013,1057,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vms</emphasis>
. Measurements as in 
<tableCitation box="[1299,1383,691,717]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="47.[151,239,457,483]" captionText="TABLE 1. Measurements (in mm) of species treated in this paper. Abbreviations used: TL = total length; HL = head length (along midline); HW = head width (at temples); PRW = prothorax width; PTW = pterothorax width; AW = abdominal width (at segment V). Note: many specimens had distorted abdomens, as noted below; consequently, the TL of many specimens could not be measured. Mean values are given in parentheses only where 10 or more individuals were measured. N = number of specimens examined." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,969]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,727,753]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet is derived from Latin “ 
<emphasis box="[819,907,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">saburro</emphasis>
” for “I ballast; I fill”, with the arbitrary ending “ 
<emphasis box="[164,209,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">-ata</emphasis>
”. This is reference to the bulky-looking male genitalia and the distally broad female subgenital plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
